EDA on Fraud Detection¶

Objective¶

Main objective behind this notebook is to get an insight of the data and to explore different aspects of it.

Content¶

    1. Load libraries and Read data
      • 1.1. Load libraries
      • 1.2. Read data
    1. Overview
      • 2.1. Head
      • 2.2. Target
      • 2.3. Missing values
    1. Feature Engineering

Attribute Information¶

  1. step: Symbolizes a time unit in which one step equals one hour
  2. type: Represents the type of online transactions
  3. amount: The amount of the transaction
  4. nameOrig: The customer that starts the transaction
  5. oldbalanceOrg: The balance prior to the transaction
  6. newbalanceOrig: The balance after the transaction is completed
  7. nameDest: The recipient of the transaction
  8. oldbalanceDest: The recipient's starting balance prior to the transaction
  9. newbalanceDest: The recipient's new balance following the transaction
  10. isFraud: Result of transaction, either fraud or not fraud

2.3. Missing values¶

Some features contain 0 in the data. It doesn't make sense here beacuse there is no change in the old balance or the new balance in some transactions. By further looking into the data we found that it is because there are a number of factors involved in the data to correctly access the reason for the change in balance, one of them being the type feature.

def dist_plot(feature,bins):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,6))
    sns.set_palette('Set1')
    ax=sns.distplot(df_dang[feature].dropna(),hist=True,kde=True,bins=bins,label='Fraud')
    ax=sns.distplot(df_safe[feature].dropna(),hist=True,kde=True,bins=bins,label='Not Fraud')
    ax.set_xlabel(None)
    ax.legend()
    plt.title(feature,pad=20)
    plt.show()

Now we will perform ANOVA F statistics test on our data. Since F statistics is greater than 3.95, so the features are significant.

In [18]:
def select_features(X_train, y_train, X_test):
    # configure to select all features
    fs = SelectKBest(score_func=f_classif, k='all')
    # learn relationship from training data
    fs.fit(X_train, y_train)
    # transform train input data
    X_train_fs = fs.transform(X_train)
    # transform test input data
    X_test_fs = fs.transform(X_test)
    return X_train_fs, X_test_fs, fs

Now we will try to scale the data.

In [22]:
def skewing(feature_new,feature):
    df[feature_new] = preprocessing.scale(boxcox(df[feature]+1)[0])
    figure = plt.figure(figsize=(15, 6))
    plt.hist(df[feature] ,facecolor='blue',alpha=0.75) 
    plt.title(feature +' Before Skewing',pad=20)
    figure = plt.figure(figsize=(15, 6))
    plt.hist(df[feature_new], facecolor = 'red', alpha=0.5)
    plt.title(feature +' After Skewing',pad=20)
    plt.show()
